revision.text:
'''Ballet of the 20th Century''' ({{lang-fr|Ballet du XXme Siècle}}), was a [[ballet]] and [[contemporary dance]] company in [[Brussels]], [[Belgium]]<ref name="Millard2014">{{cite book|author=Max Millard|title=100 New Yorkers of the 1970s: Revised Edition of Original Version|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rAJ1BAAAQBAJ&pg=PT50|date=9 September 2014|publisher=otbebookpublishing|isbn=978-3-95676-686-2|pages=50–}}</ref> in 1960, by the French/Swiss choreographer [[Maurice Béjart]].<ref name="Garafola2005">{{cite book|author=Lynn Garafola|title=Legacies of Twentieth-Century Dance|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7gIDy6ait3IC&pg=PA192|date=28 January 2005|publisher=Wesleyan University Press|isbn=978-0-8195-6674-4|pages=192–}}</ref> For many years it was the official dance company of the [[La Monnaie|Théâtre Royal de la Monnaie]].
The company was known for including South and East Asian elements in its performances.<ref name="BrownstoneFranck1991">{{cite book|author1=David M. Brownstone|author2=Irene M. Franck|title=20th century culture: a dictionary of the arts and literature of our time|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZZQUAQAAIAAJ|date=1 May 1991|publisher=Prentice Hall|isbn=978-0-13-210519-4|page=36}}</ref>
==History== Bejart had previously founded a company in Paris, which he named first Les Ballets de l'Étoile, and later Ballet Théâtre de Maurice Bejart. When he moved to Brussels in 1960,<ref name="Luck1998">{{cite book|author=Steve Luck|title=The American Desk Encyclopedia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o8MdoOd6pOcC&pg=PA90|date=22 October 1998|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-521465-9|pages=90–}}</ref> he relocated the company and renamed it Ballet du XXme Siècle.<ref name="Inc.2008">{{cite book|author=Encyclopædia Britannica, Inc.|title=Britannica Concise Encyclopedia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ea-bAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA191|date=1 May 2008|publisher=Encyclopædia Britannica, Inc.|isbn=978-1-59339-492-9|pages=191–}}</ref> It was eventually dissolved when Bejart moved to [[Switzerland]] to form [[Béjart Ballet]] in [[Lausanne]] in 1987.
