{{about|the physical object|other uses|Bookend (disambiguation)|the [[Simon & Garfunkel]] album|Bookends (album)|the company|Bookstop (company)}}
{{Refimprove|date=March 2014}}
[[File:Black metal bookend.jpg|200px|thumb|right|A simple sheetmetal bookend]]

Common in [[libraries]], bookstores, and homes, the '''bookend''' is an object tall, sturdy, and heavy enough, when placed at either end of a row of upright [[book]]s, to support or [[buttress]] them.   Heavy bookends—made of [[wood]], [[bronze]], [[marble]], and even large [[geode]]s—have been used for centuries; the simple sheetmetal bookend  (originally patented in 1877 by William Stebbins Barnard)<ref>{{cite web|title=Patent US186974|url=http://www.google.com/patents/US186974}}</ref> uses the weight of the books standing on its foot to clamp the bookend's tall brace against the last book's back; in libraries, simple metal brackets are often used to support the end of a row of books. Elaborate and decorative bookends are not uncommon as elements in [[home decor]]. 

== See also ==
* [[Bookend terrace]], a bookend effect in the design of terraced houses.


