{{short description|painting by Jean-Auguste-Dominique Ingres}}
{{italic title}}
[[File:The Envoys of Agamemnon by Ingres.jpg|thumb|250px]]
'''''The Ambassadors of Agamemnon in the tent of Achilles''''' is an 1801 painting by [[Jean-Auguste-Dominique Ingres]], produced for the [[Prix de Rome]] competition. It is now in the [[École nationale supérieure des beaux-arts]] in [[Paris]].

It shows an episode from Homer's ''[[Iliad]]'', in which [[Achilles]] refuses to listen to the envoys sent by [[Agamemnon]] to convince him back into the [[Trojan War]]. The topic assigned for the artists competing for the Prix de Rome in 1801 was the warriors' procession toward battle; Ingres' interpretation of the subject characteristically emphasized a moment of psychological drama instead of physical action.<ref>Condon et al. 1983, p. 12.</ref> The work was intended as a demonstration of Ingres' mastery of the human figure in classical history painting – [[Odysseus]] is shown in a red cloak derived from a sculpture by Pseudo-Phidias. 

The painting is in the neo-classical style and belongs to the school of [[Jacques-Louis David]], in whose studio Ingres had trained. It also shows new influences from [[John Flaxman]], whose work had just had its first [[Paris]]ian exhibition.<ref name="Adams2016">{{cite book|author=Arron Adams|title=Ingres: His Palette|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g1D_CwAAQBAJ&pg=PT5|date=18 April 2016|publisher=Arron Adams|isbn=978-605-04-2285-6|pages=5}}</ref>

